Here’s a comprehensive list of notable quotes from John Maynard Keynes, one of the most influential economists of the 20th century, primarily focusing on his key works such as *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money* and *A Tract on Monetary Reform*. These quotes cover his insights into economics, government policy, the nature of markets, and human behavior.

### **On Economics and Economic Theory**
1. "The ideas of economists and political philosophers, both when they are right and when they are wrong, are more powerful than is commonly understood." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
2. "In the long run, we are all dead." — *A Tract on Monetary Reform*
3. "The difficulty lies not so much in developing new ideas as in escaping from old ones." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
4. "Markets can remain irrational longer than you can remain solvent." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
5. "The importance of money flows from it being a link between the present and the future." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
6. "When my information changes, I alter my conclusions. What do you do, sir?" — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
7. "There is no harm in being sometimes wrong—especially if one is promptly found out." — *Essays in Biography*
8. "Capitalism is the extraordinary belief that the nastiest of men, for the nastiest of motives, will somehow work for the benefit of all." — *Essays in Persuasion*
9. "The engine which drives enterprise is not thrift, but profit." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
10. "The long run is a misleading guide to current affairs. In the long run, we are all dead." — *A Tract on Monetary Reform*

### **On Government and Policy**
11. "The government should pay people to dig holes in the ground and then fill them up." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
12. "Government machinery has been described as a marvelous labor-saving device which enables ten men to do the work of one." — *Essays in Persuasion*
13. "The state will have to exercise a guiding influence on investment, partly because private investment decisions are often based on unstable expectations." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
14. "A large proportion of our positive activities depend on spontaneous optimism rather than on a mathematical expectation." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
15. "The avoidance of taxes is the only intellectual pursuit that still carries any reward." — *Essays in Persuasion*
16. "For the engine which drives enterprise is not thrift, but profit." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
17. "If the Treasury were to fill old bottles with banknotes, bury them at suitable depths in disused coal mines… there need be no more unemployment." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
18. "The difficulty lies, not in the new ideas, but in escaping from the old ones." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
19. "I work for a government I despise for ends I think criminal." — *Essays in Persuasion*
20. "Governments should aim for growth, full employment, and price stability." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*

### **On Employment and Unemployment**
21. "The level of employment is determined not by the level of wages but by the level of aggregate demand." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
22. "It is better that a man should tyrannize over his bank balance than over his fellow citizens." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
23. "A fall in wages tends to cause unemployment, not prevent it." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
24. "The importance of reducing unemployment cannot be overstated. It affects not only those directly affected but the whole economy." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
25. "Unemployment is not the result of excessive wages but of insufficient demand for goods and services." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
26. "The outstanding faults of the economic society in which we live are its failure to provide for full employment and its arbitrary and inequitable distribution of wealth and incomes." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
27. "To cure unemployment, we need to boost aggregate demand by increasing public spending." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
28. "I can see no plausible excuse for any degree of unemployment whatsoever, except what is due to labor disputes." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
29. "Unemployment is a worse evil than inflation." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
30. "The demand for labor depends not only on the wage rate, but on the level of investment." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*

### **On Capitalism and Socialism**
31. "The love of money as a possession—as distinguished from the love of money as a means to the enjoyments and realities of life—will be recognized for what it is, a somewhat disgusting morbidity." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
32. "The decadent international but individualistic capitalism, in the hands of which we found ourselves after the war, is not a success." — *The Economic Consequences of the Peace*
33. "Capitalism is the belief that the nastiest of men, for the nastiest of motives, will somehow work for the benefit of all." — *Essays in Persuasion*
34. "The businessman is only tolerable as long as his gains can be regarded as rewards for skill and daring." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
35. "Socialism and Communism spring from our understanding that capitalism's inequalities and instabilities demand rectification." — *Essays in Persuasion*
36. "The class war will find me on the side of the educated bourgeoisie." — *Essays in Persuasion*
37. "The invisible hand of the market always corrects itself, but only after it has created damage that affects many." — *Essays in Persuasion*
38. "Lenin is said to have declared that the best way to destroy the capitalist system was to debauch the currency." — *The Economic Consequences of the Peace*
39. "The world will not much longer tolerate the unemployment which… is associated… with present-day capitalistic individualism." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
40. "In many ways, capitalism has failed the majority." — *Essays in Persuasion*

### **On Money and Inflation**
41. "There is no subtler, no surer means of overturning the existing basis of society than to debauch the currency." — *The Economic Consequences of the Peace*
42. "The inflationist school have a very different outlook from that of the deflationist school." — *A Tract on Monetary Reform*
43. "Money is not everything, but it has the ability to create its own laws of behavior." — *A Tract on Monetary Reform*
44. "The rise and fall of interest rates shape the economy's future more than any other single variable." — *A Tract on Monetary Reform*
45. "Inflation is unjust and deflation is inexpedient." — *A Tract on Monetary Reform*
46. "The boom, not the slump, is the right time for austerity at the Treasury." — *Collected Writings of John Maynard Keynes*
47. "Inflation does not make it easier to pay off debts; it makes it more difficult." — *A Tract on Monetary Reform*
48. "When the capital development of a country becomes a by-product of the activities of a casino, the job is likely to be ill-done." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
49. "The avoidance of taxes is the only intellectual pursuit that still carries any reward." — *Essays in Persuasion*
50. "A rise in the rate of interest is only one way by which the investor can be compensated for bearing risk." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*

### **On Human Behavior and Psychology in Economics**
51. "The social object of skilled investment should be to defeat the dark forces of time and ignorance which envelop our future." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
52. "Human nature desires quick results, there is no patience for long-term thinking in investment." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
53. "Worldly wisdom teaches that it is better for reputation to fail conventionally than to succeed unconventionally." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*
54. "The day is not far off when the economic problem will take the back seat where it belongs." — *Essays in Persuasion*
55. "Most men love money and security more, and creation and construction less, as they get older." — *The Economic Consequences of the Peace*
56. "A sound banker, alas, is not one who foresees danger and avoids it, but one who, when he is ruined, is ruined in a conventional and orthodox way along with his fellows." — *Essays in Persuasion*
57. "Speculation is the term for dealing with things you don

’t understand." — *The General Theory of Employment, Interest, and Money*

This list encapsulates some of Keynes' most profound economic thoughts, touching on markets, government intervention, unemployment, money, and the role of human psychology in economic activity. His ideas remain crucial in understanding modern macroeconomic theory and policy.
